<p align="center"><h2><span id="title">Maximum Entropy Modelling (MAXENT) - GUI </span></h2><img id="icon" src="../icons/maxent.png" /></p>

<p><span id="section">Brief Description</span></p>

<p>The Multivariate Environmental Similarity Surfaces (MESS) is an index that represents how similar a point in space is to a reference set of points, with respect to a set of predictor variables (Elith et al 2010). 
<p><
This processing function attempts to start the graphical interface of MAXENT directly, thus allowing more direct control of the input features.

<p><span id="section">Parameters</span></p>
<ul>
	<li><p>
		<span>[param] Input Vector Layer: </span>Point localities of species occurences</p>
	</li>
	<li><p>
		<span>[param] Input Vector Field: </span>Species name inside the vector layer </p>
	</li>
	<li><p>
		<span> Output Results: </span>The generated prediction + MAXENT results are automatically loaded into QGIS after execution. A high value of the function at a particular grid cell indicates that the grid cell is predicted to have suitable conditions for that species.  The computed model is a probability distribution over all the grid cells </p>
	</li>	
</ul>
<p><span id="section">Notes</span></p>
	<p><ul>
<li>Results are saved in the <b> work folder <b>, which can be set in the Processing Options</li>
<li>Intermediate file conversions are saved in the <b> temp folder <b>, which can be set in the Processing Options</li>

</ul></p>

<p><span id="section">Literature</span></p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Elith J., Kearney M., & Phillips S. 2010. The art of modelling range-shifting species. Met. Ecol. Evol 1 :330-342.</li>
</ul>

</p>

